Parses CLI arguments and dispatches the appropriate workflow (scan, check, prune, update, or stop-hook mode). Entry point for the binary; everything before actual work happens here.

Five mutually exclusive operations: `--dry-run` lists target files without calling the agent; `--check` recomputes hashes and reports staleness; `--prune` deletes orphaned artifacts; `--update` runs prune‚Üícheck‚Üírebuild selectively; `--stop-hook` emits a `systemMessage` JSON payload only if staleness is detected, always exits 0. Full scan is the default when none are set. `--stop-hook` conflicts with dry-run, check, update, and prune; `--prune` conflicts with dry-run and check; `--update` conflicts with dry-run. Both `leaf_model` and `rollup_model` are required and passed to the agent.

`dispatch(agent, cli, out)` validates the target directory, constructs a `Models` struct with both model names, then branches to `update_run` or `scan_run` and renders results. `stop_hook(dir, out)` short-circuits if staleness is empty‚Äîreturns `Ok` without writing‚Äîotherwise writes JSON with key `"systemMessage"`. `check(cli, out)` and `prune(cli, out)` are thin wrappers around `check_run` and `prune_run` that render their output. `list_targets(cli, out)` uses `walk_dir` and writes filenames one per line. All public functions take a `Path` or `Cli`, validate it exists via `validate_dir`, and propagate errors without retry; I/O errors on `out` are wrapped as `stdout_err`.